[1] Texas: feline, raccoon
Date: Wed 12 May 2010
Source: Burnet Bulletin [edited]
<http://www.burnetbulletin.com/view/full_story/7394827/article-Two-rabies-cases-confirmed-in-Rio-Llano-subdivision?instance=llano_news>


The Llano County Sheriff's Office and Texas Department of State
Health Services Laboratory confirmed 2 animals that recently died
near the city of Llano were infected with rabies.

Authorities said Thursday [6 May 2010] that both a black cat, which
died Monday [3 May 2010] on Rio Llano Drive West, and a raccoon,
which was killed by a rancher's dog on Sunday [?9 May 2010] on CR
201B, were infected with rabies.

Rio Llano Drive West is located in the Rio Llano subdivision just
west of the city of Llano on SH 29, and CR 201B is located a few
miles east of the city on SH 29.

There has been one other rabies case so far this year [2010]
involving a skunk in Babyhead in March.

Janie Crumpler, animal control officer for the Llano County Sheriff's
Office, said the 2 recent cases put the county ahead of the total
number of rabies cases for all of last year [2009].

For more information, contact either the Llano County Animal Control
at 325.247.5767 or the Texas Department of State Health Services
Zoonosis Control Program at 254.778.6744.

For the full story, see The Llano County Journal at
<http://llanobuzz.com/view/full_story/7320864/article-Rabies-case-confirmed-in-Rio-Llano-subdivision?>.

[Byline: Michael Freeman]

